{"title":"TwinTac: A Wide-Range, Highly Sensitive Tactile Sensor with Real-to-Sim Digital Twin Sensor Model","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Non-optical tactile sensors often trade off sensitivity for range (or vice versa), limiting their usefulness in manipulation that spans delicate touch to high-force contacts.","method":"PhysTac integrates eight MEMS pressure taxels (CPS135B-1500D) beneath an Ecoflex 00-31 elastomer, multiplexed over I2C (55 Hz) to achieve both ultra-high sensitivity and a wide pressure range. The sensor provides 0.01 kPa resolution over 50–1500 kPa, detects forces as low as 0.007 N and as high as 212 N, and exhibits a linear sensitivity of ~7.24 kPa/N. A radial basis function interpolation reconstructs a continuous spatial pressure map from the 8 taxels, enabling coarse shape discrimination despite the sparse array. (Supported: lines 60–75, 62–63, 138–140)."},{"problem":"There is a lack of high-fidelity simulators for non-optical tactile sensors, hindering simulation-driven policy learning and data generation.","method":"DigiTac is a digital twin built via a Real2Sim pipeline: an FEM-based elastomer model is created in Isaac Gym (soft-body mesh with 7636 vertices), and synchronized real/sim data are collected (FEM node positions/stresses X, simulated force F_sim, real MEMS outputs S, real force F_real). Dynamic Time Warping aligns real and simulated sequences. To map FEM outputs to sensor readings, the method aggregates Von Mises stress features from a 609-node subset located above the 8 taxels and feeds them to an MLP trained with L1 loss (AdamW, noise injection). The model reproduces PhysTac with an average error of 5.95% of the maximum contact pressure. (Supported: lines 80–87, 94–107, 110–123, 116–121, 152)."},{"problem":"Learning from limited real tactile data yields poor performance for downstream tasks like object/indenter classification.","method":"Using DigiTac, the authors synthesize time-series tactile signals by varying indentation depths, speeds, and rotation angles, and train a time-series Transformer classifier on hybrid data. With 7 indenters, combining 20 real trials and 96 simulated trials per indenter in training (testing on 20 real trials) boosts accuracy from 33.57% (real-only) to 95.0% (hybrid), demonstrating effective Sim2Real augmentation by the digital twin. (Supported: lines 156–183)."}]}
